1. Landing Page
This is the main public-facing landing page for the Postal AI service. It is designed to be clean and impactful, immediately communicating the product's purpose. At the top, a simple navigation bar contains the "Postal AI" logo and a "Sign In" button for returning users. The central focus is a large hero section with a visually relevant background image depicting mail sorting slots. Overlaid on this image is the product name "Postal AI" in a large, bold font, followed by the descriptive tagline, "Revolutionizing mail sorting with artificial intelligence." A prominent blue "Get Started" button serves as the primary call-to-action, inviting new users to engage with the service.
2. Login Page
This page provides a straightforward and secure way for existing users to access the system. It features a minimalist design to eliminate distractions. The header displays the "Postal AI" logo. The main content is a centrally aligned login form contained within a clean white card. The form is titled "Login" and includes a prompt, "Please enter your credentials to continue." It provides standard input fields for "Username" and "Password," each accompanied by a relevant icon. A full-width blue "Login" button at the bottom allows the user to submit their credentials and enter the application.
3. Admin Dashboard
This is the home screen for an authenticated administrator. The top navigation bar clearly outlines the admin's capabilities with links for "Home" (currently active), "Manage Staff," "View Sorted History," and "Logout." The main body of the page is minimalistic, displaying a large, personalized greeting: "Welcome Admin." This page acts as a central hub from which the administrator can navigate to all management functions. A footer at the bottom contains the copyright information for the application.
4. Manage Staff Page
This page allows administrators to oversee staff accounts. The navigation bar indicates that the "Manage Staff" section is active. The page is titled "Manage Staff" and features a primary action button, "Add New Staff." In the background, a table is structured to list existing staff members with columns for "SI. No," "Full Name," "Phone," "Username," and "Password." Overlaid on the screen is an "Add New Staff Member" modal, which is used to create new user accounts. The modal contains input fields for "Full Name," "Phone Number," "Username," "Password," and "Joined Date." The user can complete the action by clicking "Add Staff" or exit by clicking "Cancel."
5. Admin - View Sorted History
This page provides administrators with a comprehensive audit trail of all sorting activities. The navigation highlights "View Sorted History" as the active page. It includes powerful filtering options at the top, allowing the admin to narrow results by a date range ("From" and "To") and a search bar to find entries by "staff name or pincode." The main content area is a table designed to display the history with columns for "SL. NO," "PINCODE," "BIN NAME," "STAFF NAME," "SORTING DATE & TIME," and "STATUS." The screen currently shows a "No history found" message, indicating the empty state before any data is filtered or available.
6. Staff Dashboard
This is the main landing page for an authenticated staff member, distinct from the admin view. The navigation bar is tailored to the staff role, offering links to "Home" (active), "Upload/Capture Image," "View Bins," "View Sorted Items," and "Logout." These options reflect an operational workflow focused on the core task of sorting mail. Similar to the admin dashboard, the central area displays a large, welcoming message: "Welcome Staff." The footer contains the standard copyright notice.
7. Upload/Capture Image Page
This is the primary workspace for a staff member to begin the mail sorting process. The page, titled "Upload or Capture Postal Letter Image," offers two methods for input: an "Upload Image" card with a "Choose Image" button and a "Capture Image" card with an "Open Camera" button. On the right, an "Image Queue" panel lists all the images that have been added (e.g., Picture1, Picture2), with an option to remove each one. Once images are queued, the user clicks the central "Start Processing" button to initiate the AI analysis. A note at the bottom reminds the user that "The pincode on the image should be valid and clearly visible for accurate sorting."
8. Processing Results and Verification
After the staff member initiates processing, this modal appears, titled "Processing Completed." It presents the results of the AI's optical character recognition (OCR). A table shows the "PICTURE," the "EXTRACTED ADDRESS," and the "PINCODE" for each uploaded image. This screen highlights a crucial part of the workflow: handling exceptions. One of the items is marked with an "Error," and the system prompts the user to "Enter Pincode" manually. This human-in-the-loop design ensures accuracy even when the AI cannot read an address. The final action is to click the "Sort" button.
9. Live Sorting Animation
This page provides a real-time visual representation of the physical or digital sorting process. Titled "Live Sorting Animation," it shows an animated envelope with its identified pincode ("679303") moving towards its corresponding destination bin. The status "Sorting to Bin 679303..." confirms the action. On the right, a status panel displays the current state of various bins, showing "Bin 679303" now contains "1 item," while "Bin 679304" and the "Error Bin" are empty. A "Re-sort" button offers a way to restart or correct the process.
10. Bin Overview
This page gives staff a high-level overview of all sorting bins. It uses a clean, grid-based layout where each white card represents a specific bin (e.g., "Bin 679303," "Bin 679304," etc.). Each card displays the bin number and features an "Open Bin" button. This interface allows staff to quickly see all available bins and select one to view its contents in more detail.
11. Bin Details View
When a user clicks "Open Bin" from the overview page, this modal appears, providing a detailed look at the contents of a specific bin (e.g., "Bin 679303"). It presents a table listing all the sorted items within that bin, with columns for "SL. NO," "ADDRESS," and "PINCODE." This view is essential for verification, packing, and dispatching mail. Functionality includes a "Download PDF" button to generate a manifest and a "Close" button to return to the Bin Overview screen.
12. Staff - View Sorted History
This is the staff-facing version of the sorted history, titled "Sorted History – Today's Records." It allows staff to review their own sorting activity. It features a simple search bar to "Search by bin name." The results are displayed in a table with columns for "SL. NO," "BIN NAME," "ADDRESS," "PINCODE," and "TIME." Unlike the admin view, this history is focused on the items and their destinations rather than the staff member who performed the sort, making it a tool for operational review rather than personnel management.
